any voices
of dissent?

17:34.186 --> 17:35.554 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Yes.

17:35.588 --> 17:37.723 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are few and far between,
but they are
important to listen to.

17:37.757 --> 17:41.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I spoke to one dissenter, as
he calls
himself, just a few hours ago.

17:41.961 --> 17:43.829 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
His name is Carlos Miraros
Falcon (ph).

17:43.863 --> 17:47.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says there is no freedom of
speech and
no freedom of multiple parties.

17:47.867 --> 17:54.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what that means, Hari, is
that the criticism
of the government remains rare
and that the

17:54.640 --> 17:57.376 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
opposition remains fractured.

17:57.410 --> 18:01.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I asked him whether there is
any chance
of change now that Fidel Castro
is dead.

18:01.547 --> 18:03.282 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He said most likely not.

18:03.316 --> 18:06.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's because Fidel's younger
brother Raul
has been running the country as
president

18:06.786 --> 18:08.421 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
since 2008.

18:08.454 --> 18:10.690 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But he did point to one date,
2018.

18:10.723 --> 18:13.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is the year that Raul
Castro promises
to step down.

18:13.426 --> 18:14.660 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One of two things could happen
there.

18:14.694 --> 18:17.096 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He will step down, but he will
remain head
of the party.

18:17.129 --> 18:18.898 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That means more status question.

18:18.931 --> 18:23.336 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Or it is possible, this
dissident said, that
Raul could step down and there
could be an

18:23.369 --> 18:25.137 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
opposition leader who emerges.

18:25.171 --> 18:28.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: When you talk
to people
on the route, they're very
quickly aware that

18:28.374 --> 18:29.875 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you're an American.

18:29.909 --> 18:33.813 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Does the conversation walk into
the territory
of the new president-elect?

18:33.846 --> 18:38.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Look, I think
that there have
been changes over the last few
years.

18:38.951 --> 18:42.054 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And more Americans have been
here, so they're
more used to us.

18:42.088 --> 18:47.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Certainly, there is some fear of
president-elect
Trump, most specifically because
there is

18:47.093 --> 18:52.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mostly unanimity over the deal
that Raul Castro
and President Obama struck in
the last couple

18:52.865 --> 18:57.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
years, a kind of detente, and
they don't want
president-elect Trump to take
that away.

18:57.269 --> 19:01.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But critics do point out one
thing, that there
have been four times as many
detentions this

19:01.407 --> 19:04.577 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
year already as in all of 2010.

19:04.610 --> 19:08.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's according to the Cuban
Human Rights
and National Reconciliation
Commission.

19:08.581 --> 19:13.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And those people who point that
out point
to president-elect Trump's
tweets saying that

19:13.152 --> 19:16.622 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he would terminate the deal
unless Cuba is
willing to improve it.

19:16.655 --> 19:21.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are some people who are
hoping he actually
does that, but, in general,
people want the

19:21.060 --> 19:22.695 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
trend of the last few years to
continue.

19:22.728 --> 19:27.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Nick Schifrin
joining us
from Havana tonight, thank you.

19:27.666 --> 19:36.075 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Thanks, Hari.

19:36.108 --> 19:41.113 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

19:41.147 --> 19:46.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": a
leading Republican
senator on bringing a divisive
Congress together

19:46.318 --> 19:52.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to work with Donald Trump;
high-tech innovations
from the salad bowl of the
world; and coping

19:52.925 --> 19:58.097 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with parents who divorce later
in life.

19:58.130 --> 20:03.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now we are joined by former
Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, who served
in the Clinton

20:03.702 --> 20:05.504 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
administration, and Stephen
Hadley.

20:05.538 --> 20:09.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was a national security
adviser to President
George W. Bush.

20:09.408 --> 20:14.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Together, they have chaired an
ambitious project
called the Middle East Strategy
Task Force

20:14.647 --> 20:21.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that spent nearly two years
looking at that
troubled region's problems and
devising potential

20:21.220 --> 20:23.189 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
solutions.

20:23.222 --> 20:27.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From its base at the Atlantic
Council, a Washington
think tank, the task force
released its final

20:27.259 --> 20:29.061 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
report today.

20:29.095 --> 20:32.098 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we welcome you both of you
back to the
"NewsHour."

20:32.131 --> 20:33.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Secretary Albright, to you
first.

20:33.599 --> 20:36.602 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ambitious goal, doing something
about the
Middle East.

20:36.635 --> 20:38.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Remind us what you thought you
were going
to accomplish here.

20:38.838 --> 20:40.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT, Former U.S.
Secretary
of State: Well, we were looking
at region

20:40.739 --> 20:46.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that we know is very important
to the United
States and obviously to the
world, and trying

20:46.479 --> 20:51.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to take a much deeper look at
the Middle East,
instead of kind of doing
Band-Aids or fire

20:51.851 --> 20:59.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
drills, and looking at what can
be done to
make things less dangerous, to
deal with America's

20:59.792 --> 21:05.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
national interests, which have
to do with
our friends and allies, nuclear
proliferation,

21:05.297 --> 21:07.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
how to deal with terrorism.

21:07.266 --> 21:12.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I'm very proud of what we
did, because
we spent a lot of time looking
at the local

21:12.705 --> 21:17.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
situation, instead of telling
them what to
do and doing kind of what
Western powers have

21:17.977 --> 21:22.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
done for a hundred years, is to
get a better
sounding of what's happening in
the region

21:22.948 --> 21:24.450 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
itself.

21:24.483 --> 21:26.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stephen Hadley,
you're calling
it a new strategic approach.

21:26.986 --> 21:28.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What's different about it from
what's happening
now?

21:28.854 --> 21:31.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN HADLEY, Former U.S.
National Security
Adviser: Well, as Madeleine
said, we have

21:31.657 --> 21:35.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
had a century where outside
parties have tried
to arrange things in the Middle
East, and

21:35.861 --> 21:37.630 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
generally not very successfully.

21:37.663 --> 21:42.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What We have tried to do was
listen to voices
in the Middle East as to what
their vision

21:42.101 --> 21:44.103 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was for the future.

21:44.136 --> 21:49.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we found was, they had a
vision that there
are people, entrepreneurs, both
social entrepreneurs,

21:49.608 --> 21:53.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
business entrepreneurs, that are
making change
from the bottom up.

21:53.078 --> 22:00.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there are governments like
the UAE and
Tunisia and Saudi Arabia and
Jordan that are

22:00.186 --> 22:05.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
actually trying to move in a
direction and
take initiative for themselves.

22:05.591 --> 22:11.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the new strategic approach
is, let's follow
the lead of governments and
people in the

22:11.931 --> 22:16.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
region and have a supporting
role from the
outside, rather than the
reverse.

22:16.035 --> 22:19.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: One of the first
things you
recommend, Secretary Albright,
is a new security

22:19.438 --> 22:25.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
approach to the four countries
that have civil
wars under way right now, hot
wars going on.

22:26.011 --> 22:31.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You call, among other things,
for a stepped-up
military presence on the part of
the United

22:31.450 --> 22:33.285 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
States.

22:33.319 --> 22:38.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Why do you think something like
this can happen,
given President Obama's
reluctance to do this

22:38.290 --> 22:40.226 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
over the last eight years?

22:40.259 --> 22:43.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT: Well, I
think it's been
evident that we can't just do
things diplomatically.

22:43.896 --> 22:49.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We do want to have a political
solution to
many of the issues, obviously
Syria.

22:49.401 --> 22:54.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there has to be some way to
resolve the
civil wars.

22:54.106 --> 23:01.413 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And some of it may take
additional American,
not ground forces, but, in fact,
greater support

23:01.447 --> 23:08.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the rebel groups through
special forces,
maybe some standoff approach to
it, working

23:08.220 --> 23:15.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with the allies, with the
coalition on some
issues from the air,
establishing a safe zone,

23:15.294 --> 23:20.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and that you can't just decide,
at least we
thought, working with our
advisers, that the

23:20.399 --> 23:25.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
United States can just turn its
back on the
place, because the shorthand for
it is, there

23:25.638 --> 23:30.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is a crisis in the Middle East,
but it's also
from the Middle East, that's
affecting us

23:31.010 --> 23:32.711 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
all.

23:32.745 --> 23:35.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do you have
reason to believe,
Stephen Hadley, that the
president-elect,

23:35.447 --> 23:38.817 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Donald Trump, is going to be
interested in
an approach like this?

23:38.851 --> 23:42.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, given what he said on
the campaign
trail, that's not at all clear,
is it?

23:42.288 --> 23:46.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN HADLEY: Well, one of the
things he
said was that we need to do more
to defeat

23:46.425 --> 23:50.396 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ISIS and al-Qaida, Da'esh and
al-Qaida.

23:50.429 --> 23:54.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was critical of the past
administration,
thought they had not done
enough.

23:54.366 --> 23:59.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We recommend expanding and
accelerating what
we're doing against Da'esh and
al-Qaida.

23:59.672 --> 24:02.841 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was very critical of what
Iran has done
in the region.

24:02.875 --> 24:08.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We believe that, if we step up
what we're
doing against Da'esh and al
Qaeda in both

24:08.113 --> 24:13.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Iraq and Syria, that will put
some limitations
on what the Iranians can, quite
frankly, some

24:13.385 --> 24:16.055 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
limitations on what the Russians
can do.

24:16.088 --> 24:21.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And with that new leverage, you
may be in
a situation to move over time to
the kinds

24:21.327 --> 24:24.830 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of political solutions that
we're looking
for both in Iraq and in Syria.

24:24.863 --> 24:28.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do you have
reason to believe,
Secretary Albright, that Donald
Trump is going

24:28.200 --> 24:29.868 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to be interested in an approach
like this?

24:29.902 --> 24:33.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT: Well, we
have to see,
frankly.

24:33.138 --> 24:39.912 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that my own view here is
that we have
to -- he is the president-elect.

24:39.945 --> 24:46.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that, as he sees
what the issues
are, I am hopeful that he will
understand

24:46.151 --> 24:51.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the value of this approach,
which is that
we can't -- I mean, frankly, the
suggestions

24:51.523 --> 24:57.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that have been made during the
campaign don't
make much sense, because it's
either having

24:57.262 --> 25:04.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nothing to do with them or
bombing them to
-- he used an unspeakable word
-- but that

25:04.603 --> 25:07.106 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that's not consistent.

25:07.139 --> 25:11.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, therefore, what we're
advocating is that
we can't turn our back on the
Middle East,

25:11.877 --> 25:16.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that that is not good for
American national
interest, and that one does have
to deal with

25:16.815 --> 25:23.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Da'esh, but also to try to deal
with the civil
problems that are there,
especially in Syria,

25:23.489 --> 25:25.991 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
given what Assad is doing to his
own people.

25:26.024 --> 25:31.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So my feeling -- my hope, I have
to say, is
that he will pay attention to
this.

25:31.630 --> 25:33.232 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And this is a bipartisan effort.

25:33.265 --> 25:36.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm very proud to have been able
to work with
Steve Hadley on this.

25:36.568 --> 25:41.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we have taken a rational
approach
to a very, very difficult
problem.

25:41.273 --> 25:45.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You also call,
Steve Hadley,
for unleashing what you say is
the region's

25:45.411 --> 25:50.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
human and economic potential,
hand in hand
with the security measures.

25:50.749 --> 25:54.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These are the kinds of things,
education,
engaging the youth of the
region, getting

25:54.920 --> 25:59.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- giving opportunities to
women, these are
kinds of things that call for a
lot of money

25:59.892 --> 26:05.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and frankly some different both
religious
and cultural changes, don't
they?

26:05.130 --> 26:07.332 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN HADLEY: I don't think
they call for
a lot of money.

26:07.366 --> 26:11.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's one of the things I
think that we
are proud of this report,
because when you

26:11.770 --> 26:17.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
talk in Washington about the
Middle East,
it's all about Iraq and Syria
and Iran.

26:17.176 --> 26:22.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What we have found is that
there's positive
things going on, activity at the
local level,

26:22.648 --> 26:26.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
government policies that are
moving in the
right direction of empowering
their people,

26:26.819 --> 26:31.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of getting rid of regulations
that are in
the way of the kind of
entrepreneurial activity

26:31.523 --> 26:32.491 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
we're seeing.

26:32.524 --> 26:34.359 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There is some good news there.

26:34.393 --> 26:38.130 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is something that we can
work with in
order to try to get a more
peaceful and stable

26:38.163 --> 26:39.932 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Middle East.

26:39.965 --> 26:42.468 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Is there
receptivity there
in each one of these countries
for what you're

26:42.501 --> 26:44.236 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
calling for?

26:44.269 --> 26:46.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because you're talking about
these countries
working together in many ways,
which they

26:46.839 --> 26:48.574 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
haven't been willing to do.

26:48.607 --> 26:52.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT: Well, we
notice there
is kind of different levels of
receptivity.

26:52.511 --> 26:57.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I do think that many of the
countries' leaders
know that they have problems and
that they

26:57.583 --> 27:04.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
need to deal with their growing
youth population,
that the youth is actually an
asset, instead

27:04.156 --> 27:11.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of a problem, and that there is
money in the
region, and that they can help
each other.

27:11.530 --> 27:16.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the other things that
I think we
also made a point about is that
new institutions

27:16.835 --> 27:18.637 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
will make a difference,
parliaments.

27:18.670 --> 27:21.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Look, let me just say, we have
spent a lot
of time on this.

27:21.974 --> 27:25.777 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And a lot it may kind of seem
too idealistic.

27:25.811 --> 27:31.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the issue here is that
there does
need to be some humility in
dealing with this,

27:31.483 --> 27:32.451 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
taking a long-term approach.

27:32.484 --> 27:33.519 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: On the part of
the Americans?

27:33.552 --> 27:35.320 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is that what you're saying?

27:35.354 --> 27:39.491 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT: Yes,
absolutely, in terms
of knowing how difficult it is,
and deciding

27:39.525 --> 27:41.493 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to take kind of a step-by-step
approach.

27:41.527 --> 27:43.295 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's a road map, really.

